S2.T1.caption: Table 1. Steps of two-party logistic regression in VFL.
references: In VFL, we also use the SGD optimizer to update the model parameters. Table 1 lists the detailed training steps of logistic regression in secure VFL.

The secure VFL protocol works as follows.
First, participants 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} and ℬℬ\mathcal{B} initialize 𝜽𝒜superscript𝜽𝒜\boldsymbol{\theta}^{\mathcal{A}} and 𝜽ℬsuperscript𝜽ℬ\boldsymbol{\theta}^{\mathcal{B}} as vectors of random values or all 00s. Coordinator 𝒞𝒞\mathcal{C} creates an encryption key pair and sends the public key to 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} and ℬℬ\mathcal{B}. Second, in each training iteration (communication round), participant 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} randomly selects a mini-batch of indices S𝑆S and updates the distributed coefficient by averaging partial derivatives of all samples to the current coefficient. Steps 2–4 in Table 1 describe how 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} and ℬℬ\mathcal{B} collaboratively compute the gradient of the encrypted distributed loss function and update the distributed coefficient. I.e., using an additively homomorphic encryption scheme, participants 𝒜𝒜\mathcal{A} and ℬℬ\mathcal{B} compute on the encrypted intermediate outputs and generate an encrypted derivative which, when decrypted, matches with the derivative as if it had been calculated on the plaintext.

Table 6 reports the success rate as well as the number of successfully cracked samples by our attack using different numerical bases and supergroup sizes. The results show that, using a small base and group size results in the highest attack success rate, while using a large base and a large group size results in more cracked samples. The reason behind this is twofold. By using a large base and a supergroup size,
the capacity of the encoded samples ramps up. This basically requires the adversary to encode magic numbers into more samples, thus it can obtain more information about the addition terms of the gradient sum. However, the large capacity also creates a large search space for the samples in the same group, making it harder for the adversary to figure out all the right addition terms.

We use the default segmentation to get bins on all the features of the Credit dataset. Table 7 shows the percentage of the successfully inferred bin values (left and right bounds of the bin) with different sizes (ranging from 5 to 320 samples) of the auxiliary dataset. As shown in the table, for a particular feature space, the number of auxiliary samples required to infer the bounds depends on the number of data bins. The more data bins used in a feature space, the more number of auxiliary samples will be required to infer the bin values up to a satisfactory accuracy.
From Table 7, we can see that the adversary can successfully infer the left and right bounds of each bin if it knows the whole features of a few samples.
